{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Dr4HM8mZcXbVETBJuU9hpV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Key observations:\n1. Prometheus is on port 9090 internally but served externally at port 8000 (via the Service which maps 8000->9090)\n2. The Prometheus config only scrapes itself (localhost:9090)\n3. RabbitMQ has a headless service `rabbitmq-headless` with ports 5672, 15672, 15692\n4. RabbitMQ pods are `rabbitmq-0`, `rabbitmq-1`, `rabbitmq-2` in the StatefulSet\n\nThe solution is to update the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a scrape job for RabbitMQ using the headless service DNS names for the individual pods:\n- `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n- `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n- `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.<namespace>.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n\nAfter updating the ConfigMap, I need to reload Prometheus. Since it's deployed with `--web.enable-lifecycle`, I can trigger a hot-reload via the Prometheus service endpoint or restart the deployment. The quickest approach is to update the ConfigMap and then reload Prometheus.\n\nI should also verify the Prometheus service port mapping to confirm it's exposing port 9090 correctly.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1488,"cache_read_input_tokens":30051,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1488},"output_tokens":25,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"dc88e6a7-031b-4450-a546-186afe4101b4","uuid":"bcf0e9f5-484f-46e7-a5f5-45d47f36696a","request_id":"req_011Ccd9LNhXXiNR6ia2qVnnP"}
